@elibixby We have a [utility like that](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/blob/a9891abdd9a8fb83194d67c01ae0980ae395fbe9/system_tests/retry.py#L142) now for system testing.  We could move it (and maybe the error-based and result-based ones) into the library itself, which might look like:


```python
from gcloud.retry import RetryInstanceState

def _job_done(job):
    return job.state.lower() == 'done'

until_done = RetryInstanceState(_job_done)

class _BaseJob(object):
    ...
    @until_done
    def wait(self):
        self.reload()
```

@dhermes We need to factor out the `google.longrunning.operations` bit, including making the name pattern and metadata lookup bits less smelly.  If we did, then we could add an `Operation.wait` method.

@jonparrott [3898](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/issues/3898#issuecomment-361432534) 

This was the reason I did the change like that.  I thought about having text and value functions to retrieve whatever was present, but that would violate the one way of doing things.  I also thought about having separate text and value functions to retrieve only the respective text or value if it existed, but that would require the user to keep track of text or value instead of just returning what was present, which might be better in terms of design, but at the cost of less convenience.  

So I thought that this was the better choice.

@amsokol Unfortunately this is an issue with Visual Studio and not with these packages.

The `google` and `google.cloud` packages are namespace packages, so they get imported in a special way by Python. They do have `__init__.py` modules but those are typically untouched because `pth` files get added when these namespace packages get installed.

See: https://packaging.python.org/guides/packaging-namespace-packages/
